title: For Sale:  WWI German Dreyes Model 1907 .32 Pistol
postcontent: WWI German Dreyse Model 1907 .32 acp pistol. 3.5" Barrel. Some bluing wear but otherwise very nice condition. Beautiful walnut grips. One 7 round magazine included. Serial number 86XXX. Upper sideplate maked as follows: DREYSE Rheinische Metallwaaren & Maschinenfabrik ABT. SOMMERDA.The pistol had an interesting feature for the time: when the gun was ready to fire, the firing pin projected through the back of the breech block, serving as an early handgun-cocking indicator. For cleaning, the frame, receiver and slide pivoted forward on a pin in front of the trigger guard, Breaking the action open for easy cleaning. I have fired the gun, and it is surprisingly actuate and fun to shoot! No failure to feeds or malfunctions of any kind. It operates on a simple blow-back design, but of a very unusual design. The barrel is fixed to the frame (probably why it is so accurate), and the recoil mechanism is fitted above the barrel. It can be hinged and open by moving a small lever, and can completely field disassembled without tools.The blueing is in good condition, with a bright shinny barrel and good rifling. The grips look great. This would make a great addition to your pre-WWII significant arms collection.Legal transfers only (stupid WA law), although it can be sold directly to C&R FFL license holders. There is a place in south Skagit County that does transfers for $25.  I travel from time to time as far south as Seattle and more often north to Bellingham and could probably meet along the way.  I can also ship to your FFL for $30.I can send more pictures; Airmslist only allows me to post one picture.Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

title: For Sale:  Vintage H&R Self-Loading Pistol, Webley Licensed, .32 ACP w/ REAL Stag Grips!
postcontent: Harrington & Richardson H&R Self-Loading Pistol, Licensed Webley, 32Acp(7.65mm Browning) with Real Stag Grips.Nice specimen of an early H&R pistol in good condition. The blueing is in good condition, as is the rifling. I fired the gun, and it functions correctly. What really makes this gun nice is the real stag grips with H&R seal in center. These were produced from 1916 into the 1920's. Initially, the .32 was a virtual copy of the Webley 1906, with internal improvements being made by H&R to the Webley design. Featuring a concealed hammer, 3.5" barrel, eight-round capacity and both grip and slide-mounted safeties, the H&R version was an excellent weapon that never caught on with the American public. With sales slow, production was halted in 1924, but the pistol remained in H&R's catalog as late as 1939. Popular with collectors today, this is regarded by many as the highest-quality H&R firearms ever produced.This would make a great addition to your pre-WWII arms of interest collection.   Price is firm, but I may be interested in interesting antique, muzzleloading or unique firearm trades. Sorry, but I'm not interested in non-firearm trades.Legal transfers only (stupid WA law), although it can be sold directly to C&R FFL license holders. There is a place in south Skagit County that does transfers for $25. I travel from time to time as far south as Seattle and more often north to Bellingham and could probably meet along the way.
